	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>DNA testing shows that 40% of hake sold in Spain is mislabelled</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 May 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p>A team of researchers from the University of Oviedo have found that almost 40% of hake consumed in Spain is mislabelled, coming not from Europe or America, but from African waters.</p><p>Between 2004 and 2006, the researchers analysed a total of 93 packets of hake in various supermarkets. They found that 31.5% of the packets showed either the incorrect scientific name for hake or its origin. The study, published in the <i>Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry</i>, was repeated in 2010 with another 18 brands, broadly confirming the earlier results, as 38.9% of the labels contained information that was wrong.</p><p>According to the co-authors of the study, ‘the consumer pays a higher price’ for hake caught in Africa, believing that it is from the USA or the EU. For scientists, the error ‘could be’ due to confusion during the labelling process that takes place in the distribution centres. However, they note that it makes them very suspicious that ‘cheap’ hake from Africa is the only one that is labelled as the ‘expensive’ European or American versions. For the co-authors, ‘the fraud only benefits those selling the product or intermediaries, but not the fishermen or producers in Africa, whose low wages are likely to be due to the lower price of hake from that continent.’</p><p>In supermarkets and frozen-food centres in Spain, consumers pay more for European and American hake than the African alternative. For example, in 2010, each kilogram of frozen hake from South America cost on average €11.72, while the South African product was worth €6.79.</p><p>The study argues that ‘government-mandated genetic surveys of commercial hakes and the use of subsequent statements of fair trade on labels of seafood products could help to reduce fraud levels in a global market of increasingly conscious consumers sensitive to ethical issues’.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p>A team of researchers from the University of Oviedo have found that almost 40% of hake consumed in Spain is mislabelled, coming not from Europe or America, but from African waters.</p><p>Between 2004 and 2006, the researchers analysed a total of 93 packets of hake in various supermarkets. They found that 31.5% of the packets showed either the incorrect scientific name for hake or its origin. The study, published in the <i>Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry</i>, was repeated in 2010 with another 18 brands, broadly confirming the earlier results, as 38.9% of the labels contained information that was wrong.</p><p>According to the co-authors of the study, ‘the consumer pays a higher price’ for hake caught in Africa, believing that it is from the USA or the EU. For scientists, the error ‘could be’ due to confusion during the labelling process that takes place in the distribution centres. However, they note that it makes them very suspicious that ‘cheap’ hake from Africa is the only one that is labelled as the ‘expensive’ European or American versions. For the co-authors, ‘the fraud only benefits those selling the product or intermediaries, but not the fishermen or producers in Africa, whose low wages are likely to be due to the lower price of hake from that continent.’</p><p>In supermarkets and frozen-food centres in Spain, consumers pay more for European and American hake than the African alternative. For example, in 2010, each kilogram of frozen hake from South America cost on average €11.72, while the South African product was worth €6.79.</p><p>The study argues that ‘government-mandated genetic surveys of commercial hakes and the use of subsequent statements of fair trade on labels of seafood products could help to reduce fraud levels in a global market of increasingly conscious consumers sensitive to ethical issues’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<i>Fish Information &amp; Services</i>, ‘Almost 40 per cent of hake is mislabelled: study’, 11 March 2011<br/>
http://fis.com/fis/worldnews/worldnews.asp?l=e&amp;id=41123&amp;ndb=1<br/>
Scientific article abstract, ‘High level of mislabelling in Spanish and Greek hake markets suggests the fraudulent introduction of African species’, by E. García-Vazquez <i>et al</i>., <i>Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry</i>, January 2011<br/>http://www.evolutionsbiologie.uni-konstanz.de/gonpdf/16.pdf</p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Ensuring that ACP fish producers, including African hake producers, receive a fair price, should be a priority. It appears that many of the industrial fishing companies that fish in Namibian and South African waters for hake to supply EU markets are sister companies of EU-based companies fishing for European hake. In this context, it seems important to understand where this apparent fraud comes from. Using fair-trade labels designed to ensure a better price for low-paid producers may not be appropriate for this situation. What is needed in any case is more transparency along the fish-trade value chain so as to provide producers, decision-makers and consumers with a clearer idea of the different beneficiaries of fish trade and how to ensure a fair distribution of the value of the product along the supply chain. The EC proposal, in the context of the reform of the Common Organisation of the Fish Market (CMO), to set up a fish-price observatory, could be a useful tool towards achieving that, and it would be advisable for ACP countries to express their views on this topic in the CMO reform debate.</p>
		</div>
		
